05044nam a2200817Ia 9780674419070DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20131995mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013947697  a(OCoLC)1399977512  a97806744190707 a10.4159/harvard.97806744190702doi  a(DE-B1597)252788  a(OCoLC)900809173  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQL444.M315 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a595.3/711 aCulver, David C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAdaptation and Natural Selection in Caves :bThe Evolution of ‹i›Gammarus minus‹/i› /cThomas C. Kane, Daniel W. Fong, David C. Culver.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (223 p.) :billustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Caves as Evolutionary Laboratories -- t3. Gammarus minus as a Model Organism -- t4. The Ecological Theater -- t5. The Geography of Gammarus minus -- t6. Making a Case for Selection -- t7. Putting the Pieces Together -- t8. Questions of Time -- t9. Adaptation in Gammarus minus -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe harsh environment of caves--dark, damp, sparse of food--is home to a variety of "bizarre" creatures. Biologists, for their part, often treat these delicate, colorless organisms having no eyes, or at least greatly reduced eyes, as mere oddities with little to tell us about a topic as grand as evolution. Focusing on one cave-dwelling crustacean, Gammarus minus, this book shows that, to the contrary, cave life can provide a valuable empirical model for the study of evolution, particularly adaptation. Authors David Culver, Thomas Kane, and Daniel Fong marshal many years of extensive research into the genetics, ecology, morphology, and systematics of Gammarus minus. They explain how these biological factors have been shaped by physical constraints, such as the structure and development of caves and karst terrains, groundwater hydrology, and drainage basin patterns. Their work reveals the advantages of caves for studying natural selection: the highly simplified habitats found underground serve as a natural laboratory for the evolutionary biologist, and the distinctive morphological features of cave fauna provide a wealth of data on evolutionary history and natural selection. A detailed evolutionary study of a single organism in a particular environment, this book advances Gammarus minus as a paradigm for cave colonization and adaptation, and as a general case study of the role of natural selection and adaptation in evolution.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAnimais carnívoros (evolução). 0aAnimais carnívoros (evolução). 0aArthropoda. 0aCave animals. 0aNatural selection. 0aTiere (Zoologie). 4aCave animals. 4aGammarus minus -- Evolution. 4aNatural selection. 4aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aFong, Daniel W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKane, Thomas C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Science eBook Packagez9783110353549oZDB-23-HSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067441906340uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441907040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674419070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674419070/original  